    {
      "id": "cac9e492f9c871d9dd01d97a87014f0792ecb607",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-02-15 22:55:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 5.7/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/45a4c5e4-5826-11e1-9df1-5254004bbbd3).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "577cd133930e7d6b106a72bf1a499e9150ee4c67",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-02-16 01:57:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe patch can resolve VBR failure in LU-1060. As for LU-966 itself, why not consider another way: http://review.whamcloud.com/#change,2149\n\nIt fixed LU-1060 issus based on original LU-966 patch. The original LU-966 patch gave more strict check about whether the target should exist or not, which is better that strict nothing.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "996eae22e2da70da7afb5f6b1fc8915fbc176f2a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-02-16 05:04:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nI tend to think this patch is better than http://review.whamcloud.com/#change,2149 .\n\nI think we'd keep the semantics of mdt_object_find(): it just find the object, caller should call mdt_object_exists() to see if the object is existing.\n\nI'm not quite sure the root cause of LU-966, it seems that the LASSERT is only triggered when filesystem (or data) is corrupted by fsck, so this LASSERT looks proper to me (assert on external errors which we can't manage), however, to avoid crash server, we may downgrade this LASSERT into an error message and return error. (though I'm not sure if filesystem can still work properly)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d6b9369c76328041b76db91f86b2fa73cb25ebf1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 103,
        "name": "Zhenyu Xu",
        "email": "bobijam@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bobijam"
      },
      "date": "2012-02-16 05:31:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "967ba7b46eacb0d650bcd7849900d1aa4e675be5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-02-16 07:16:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\nThough I wonder if all the object existence could be done in a few centralized places, instead of all around.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "78d60e286540ee90987bba9ba9bb9f1b9cae384b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
